<title>Information about the Integration Exam</title>

<p>The integration module exam is based on the Pure-time Differential Equation module.</p>

<section><title>Material for the exam</title>

<ol>
<li><p>Solving pure-time differential equations</p>

<ol>
<li>Calculate a general solution to a pure-time differential equation as an indefinite integral, including an arbitrary constant.</li>

<li>Given an initial condition, determine the value of the constant, resulting in a specific solution. </li>

<li>Given a graph of the right hand side of a pure-time differential equation (e.g.,, a graph of <m>f(t)</m> for the equation <m>\frac{dx}{dt} = f(t)</m>), sketch a graph of the solution.  Be sure that your sketch matches the initial condition, as well as the intervals where the solution is increasing or decreasing. </li>

<li>Estimate the solution to a pure-time differential equation using the Forward Euler algorithm.</li>
</ol>
</li>


<li>
<p>Integration</p>

<ol>
<li>Calculate an indefinite integral as an antiderivative, including an arbitrary constant.</li>
<li>Calculate a definite integral, resulting in a single number.  Use the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to determine that single number from the indefinite integral.</li>
<li>Estimate a definite integral using a left or right Riemann sum.</li>
</ol>
</li>

<li>
<p>Applications of integration</p>

<ol>
<li>Compute the area between the graph of a function and the <m>x</m>-axis.</li>
<li>Use an integral to calculate the average of a quantity over an interval.</li>
<li>Use a pure time differential equation to solve for population size as a function of time.</li>
</ol>
</li>

</ol>
</section>

